commit.message: Set revert-buffer-function to that `g' refreshes the `*uptimes*' buffer

Add colours to outout and allow many parts of the output to be customised

- New faces: uptimes-header-face, uptimes-headings-face, uptimes-current-uptime-face
   and uptimes-other-uptimes-face
- New variable uptimes-heading-string allows the user to change the column headings
   ("Boot Endtime Uptime" and the 'underlining' with "=") that appear immediately
	 before each list of uptimes
- New variable uptimes-current-uptime-indicator allows the user to change the "<--"
   string that indicates the uptime of the current Emacs
- New variable uptimes-show-last-uptimes-first controls whether
   the "top n" or "last n" are shown first
- New variable uptimes-show-booted-first controls whether the "booted/ended"
   or duration of the uptime are shown first
- New variable uptimes-duration-formatter - set this to a function that
   returns a formatted duration (eg "x days, 2 hours, 3 mins, 1 second")
	 (the default uptimes-defaiult duration-formatter produces the previous
	  version's format: 'd.HH:MM:SS' as a length-12-string)
- New variable uptimes-timestamp-formatter - set this to a function that
   returns a formatted duration (eg "DD/MM/YYYY <time>")
	 (the default uptimes-default-timestamp-formatter produces the previous
	  versions' format: "YYYY-MM-DD <time>" as a length-19-string

- Remove uptimes-uptime-string -- instead use the above new variables and
   faces inside uptimes-print-uptimes
- New helper function uptimes-with-face to add a face to a string
- uptimes-print-uptimes now uses the above new variables and faces. It also
   `insert's its output rather than producing to `standard-output', and gains a
	 new first argument which is the title ("Top 10 uptimes" or "last 5 uptimes")
	 above the list
- In uptimes, -- document the format of the output, set current-buffer to *uptimes*,
   do not hardcode lenghts of uptimes-last-n and uptimes-top-n lists,

commit.message:
:zap: Don't save if we're not an interactive Emacs

I can't see a good reason why I'd ever want to track the uptimes of an Emacs
session that isn't being used by me. I also think this might be the reason
why, over time, I've been getting stray copies of the uptimes file in my
~/.emacs.d directory.

The way I have things working, I tell uptimes to keep the tracking file in
~/.local/share/emacs. But now and again I get a rogue copy will appear back
in ~/.emacs.d. Originally I thought the cause of this was the save on
startup, so f4727bd4f3421b905c5a0cc586b0d7c72389c046 was made to try and
tackle that. However, I've still being getting the issue.

I think it may be down to the fact that emacs gets called as a compiler when
I'm installing and upgrading stuff.

So, I don't know for sure this is the fix I'm looking for, but it can't
hurt.
